			if your English is fluent then there are some self-learning materials available that are not too bad (though not great), you can find some of them here:       
the online grammar tool is pretty good and not terribly expensive (I think less than CHF 50), although candidly all of the English-to-Swiss German materials I have come across are weak in their explanations of grammar.  the benefit with self-learning is that you can study and learn when your schedule permits.  the biggest hurdle with self-learning is finding an environment where Swiss German is spoken and where you can use the language enough to start building vocabulary (which is not too terribly steep a hurdle in Zurich but may be more so where you live).   
good luck!

 
			
			For those Zurich-living people who are interested in learning French, Alliance Francaise is starting new classes on Apr 27th 2009, and they still have room (I called them to check). Here's class info;       
Study material cost extra on top of that, 48 CHF I was told.    
From what she said A1 is for absolute beginners (no previous knowledge), A2 for slight but very little knowledge. A3 is when you start with future & past, and from there on out I didn't ask, I assume B1 you have some better understanding and can make yourself somewhat understood.
